{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"243514bb-e42a-49cc-8ac2-9a44cff53d27","content":"Add a `.vscode/mcp.json` file to your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- `type: \"stdio\"` means Copilot communicates via stdin/stdout\n- `command`/`args` tell VS Code how to launch your server\n- The server must speak the [MCP protocol](https://modelcontextprotocol.io) over stdio\n\nAfter adding this, restart VS Code or run **\"MCP: List Servers\"** from the command palette to verify it connects. Your server's tools will then be available in Copilot agent mode (prefixed with `@`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"964a91e9-60ce-42fd-807c-727a629f7219","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to know how to configure `mcp.json` to use their C# MCP server with GitHub Copilot in VS Code agent mode. Let me provide a concise answer based on my knowledge of VS Code MCP configuration.","outputTokens":285,"requestId":"C030:134464:1BF2572:1F935C9:6A07C2D3"},"id":"98c673e2-4b22-4966-826e-fedbf3c12e9d","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:05:33.735Z","parentId":"604b238c-d586-46b8-8215-203a8087fc59"}
